<TEXT>
vice president george bush said friday he didnt authorize 
aides comments depicting edwin meese iii as a campaign liability 
but i must say i am troubled by some of the allegations against 
the attorney general while michael dukakis pocketed the 
endorsements of six democratic governors as he moved toward his 
partys nomination 
jesse jackson the only other active candidate in the 1988 
presidential race was in california as part of an intensive 
costly effort to ambush dukakis in the june 7 seasonending 
primary 
he complained anew that he was not being treated fairly in the 
partys delegate selection process but added soothingly we need 
not speak in terms of a fight 
bush took aim at both democratic candidates as he addressed a 
republican dinner at the university of nebraska in lincoln on the 
way home from three days of campaigning in the west 
its a pleasure to be here and ill be back bush told the 
group and im not going to be outhustled by the hustler from 
chicago or from that traditional liberal democrat from 
massachusetts 
it was a clear reference to the jackson who has a home in 
chicago and dukakis the governor of massachusetts bush spokesman 
stephen hart said the vice president was talking about how hard 
he jackson has hustled it was nothing derogatory 
early in the day bush the allbutcertain republican nominee 
told reporters he would have to get on the phone and find out 
what two top aides said about the attorney general whose conduct 
is being investigated by a special prosecutor 
i havent authorized anything the vice president added as 
he campaigned in idaho 
later in billings mont bush said he had talked to the aides 
but would not characterize his conversation of meese bush said 
i know him well favorably but i must say i am troubled by some 
of the allegations i think fair play dictates that the system go 
forward and make the determination 
when asked if meese had become an albatross on his campaign 
bush said an albatross i dont think so 
he added that the independent counsel probing meeses legal 
difficulties soon will release a report and well see what it 
says its only a matter of a few days away 
the comments of the bush aides were reported in the detroit 
news the latest development in an ethical controversy that has 
provided democrats with campaign ammunition and turned meese into a 
political embarrassment in the eyes of some republican strategists 
the paper in a story published earlier in the day said peter 
teeley bushs communications director and robert teeter a senior 
campaign adviser made the comments in interviews this week in 
washington 
meese is a liability teeley was quoted as saying 
what a guy like meese does is take away the opportunity to 
discuss the issues that you really want to discuss teeley told 
the newspaper i mean you are consistently asked about meeses 
problems how you deal with it how you stand one thing or 
another and that just totally diverts attention from the message 
that you are trying to get across 
all things considered you would rather not have that problem 
going on right now teeter was reported to have said no one is 
arguing that it is a plus to have that situation going on over 
there 
meese denies any wrongdoing and says he doesnt intend to 
resign and bush has never urged him to do so 
democratic frontrunner dukakis dropped off the campaign trail 
for several days divided between his statehouse office in boston 
and a private weeekend with his wife kitty 
but he won the support of the halfdozen governors mostly in 
the west in a fresh sign that the democratic party is coalescing 
behind his candidacy despite jacksons persistent challenge 
gov dukakis has emerged as the voters choice the clear 
leader in the democratic nomination process said arkansas gov 
bill clinton described as the leader in the effort to round up the 
gubernatorial support that was announced during the day it is 
time for the party leadership to unite behind his candidacy he 
said 
other than clinton the governors adding their endorsements 
and their votes as delegates to the democratic national convention 
were govs cecil andrus of idaho steve cowper of alaska ted 
schwinden of montana george sinner of north dakota and michael 
sullivan of wyoming 
clinton said friday that he had agreed to try to put together 
a number of governors as many as were willing to come out and 
endorse before the michigan caucuses march 26 but he added 
governor dukakis felt that after michigan which he lost that 
none of us should look as if they were involved in any effort to 
stop jackson who won in michigan 
thus clinton said he and the other five governors withheld 
their endorsement until now to avoid the appearance of a 
stopjackson movement 
i was very impressed that governor dukakis and his campaign 
felt strongly enough were sensitive enough that they actually 
asked people to hold off for weeks and weeks on endorsement i 
think it shows a lot of maturity and a real determination to unify 
the party clinton said 
dukakis aides said they expected additional endorsements from 
governors in the next several days possibly including oregons 
neil goldschmidt 
while the massachusetts governor solidified his position at the 
top of the ticket backstage maneuvering continued over the vice 
presidential slot 
sen john glenn of ohio a former astronaut who failed in his 
effort to win the 1984 presidential nomination signaled he was 
available if dukakis wanted him he said he would be glad to sit 
down and discuss it but added he was not campaigning for the job 
dukakis has slightly more than 1500 delegates in the associated 
press delegate count with 2081 needed to clinch the nomination 
jackson has fewer than 1000 
jackson took note of the delegate deficit he faces and said he 
was fighting the press and pundits the party the candidate 
its not just me and him he said of dukakis its me and 
them 
he had suggested on thursday that his supporters backing of the 
eventual nominee could wax or wane depending on how he was treated 
in the allocation of convention super delegates he said 
friday we need not speak in terms of a fight we will make 
our appeals to the appropriate places 
