<TEXT>
teamsters president jackie presser 
hospitalized for a new round of cancer treatments is taking a 
leave of absence from his job just two months before his scheduled 
trial on racketeering and embezzlement charges 
presser 61 has told the 20 other members of the unions 
executive board that he will be temporarily unavailable for the 
next 120 days because of his health his attorney john climaco 
said thursday 
climaco said presser is hospitalized at the cleveland clinic in 
ohio where he is undergoing a new round of radiation treatments 
during the periods of his treatments and for a period of time 
afterwards he has been advised to rest and avoid all forms of 
stress the attorney said 
union officials declined to describe pressers condition further 
the rotund teamsters president underwent surgery in january 1987 
for lung cancer and has not returned to work full time since then 
while undergoing a series of radiation and chemotherapy treatments 
however he has made several appearances at various union 
functions including the aflcios convention last october at which 
he gave a rambling speech on the teamsters reaffiliation with the 
labor federation after a 30year absence 
the 16 millionmember union will be directed during pressers 
leave by secretarytreasurer weldon l mathis regarded as a 
possible successor to the teamsters presidency union officials 
said 
presser is expected to keep receiving his salary in various 
union positions now about 600000 annually the officials said 
when asked if presser would seek another delay of his trial on 
federal charges in connection with an alleged payrollpadding 
scheme at a teamsters local in cleveland that he also heads 
climaco answered not necessarily 
the trial already postponed several times because of pressers 
health is scheduled to open in us district court in cleveland on 
july 12 
mr presser is looking forward to his july trial and hopes he 
will be physically able to stand trial so that he can once and for 
all vindicate himself the lawyer said 
presser is accused of participating in a scheme in which two men 
with alleged organized crime ties were placed on the cleveland 
locals payroll at a cost of 700000 over several years while 
performing no work for the union 
he has pleaded innocent his attorneys contend that the fbi 
acquiesced in and encouraged the continued employment of the two 
men while it used presser as a government informant 
presser was elevated to the teamsters presidency in 1983 after 
his predecessor roy williams was convicted of conspiring to offer 
a bribe to former us sen howard cannon dnev in an effort 
defeat legislation deregulating the trucking industry 
williams is now serving a 10year prison sentence 
</TEXT>
