<TEXT>
the united states must make a much more 
ambitious effort to cut its budget deficit for the benefit of 
other countries as well as itself the international monetary fund 
says 
recent history suggests that such an approach need not create 
serious dangers of an economic downturn according to the funds 
new world economic outlook distributed this week 
the fund a consortium of 151 governments including the united 
states says continued high us deficits could trigger world 
market reactions that would sharply reduce us growth cut 
spending output and investment in other industrial countries and 
make further shifts in the value of the dollar and other currencies 
all this could occur with or without a stock market decline it 
adds 
the fund calculates that last falls crash is costing the united 
states half of one percentage point of growth equal to about 20 
billion this year and the same amount in 1989 
it said third world countries could suffer because a slowdown of 
growth in the industrial world would reduce the demand for the raw 
materials they produce at the same time the poorer countries 
would cut their imports but their exports would also fall reducing 
the income available to keep up with payments on their debts 
the fund says the us deficit was cut by 2 percent in the year 
that ended last sept 30 without any significant harm to business 
this year it points out there will be increased help to us 
business from higher exports 
