<TEXT>
brown university has added two more 
courses to the number required for graduation partially reversing 
a 19yearold move to make its curriculum more flexible 
students in the ivy league schools class of 1993 will be 
required to pass 30 courses to qualify for a bachelors degree 
robert reichley vice president for university relations said 
thursday 
the current system was adopted as part of a wideranging 
curriculum reform in 1969 the new curriculum cut the 
graduation requirement from 32 to 28 courses and abolished 
distribution requirements and the grade of f 
a student who fails a course at brown does not receive credit 
for the course but the failure is not recorded on his or her 
transcript 
the reforms were intended to allow students to experiment by 
taking courses in areas outside their major fields of study without 
worrying about failure students still paid for 32 courses but 
could fail four without penalty 
many students were not using the system as intended according 
to a study conducted by dean sheila blumstein 
of the class of 1987 44 percent took 30 or fewer courses and 
twothirds of the students graduating with fewer than 32 courses 
did not even register for 32 blumstein found 
blumstein and reichley said the change was essentially a 
finetuning of the system and does not represent a major retreat 
reichley said the change has nothing to do with us education 
secretary william bennetts wellpublicized call for a return to 
basics in us higher education 
brown still does not require students to take specific classes 
outside their majors or fulfill distribution requirements by 
taking classes in several specified fields reichley said many top 
schools do have those requirements 
brown officials have cited the 1969 reforms as one reason the 
university has become among the nations most popular and most 
competitive 
blumstein said she thinks the tougher graduation requirement 
will have little effect on browns popularity and said students 
seem to support it 
the change brings brown more into line with requirements at 
other top universities 
harvard requires the equivalent of 32 semesterlong classes for 
graduation while yale requires 36 at princeton liberal arts 
students are required to take 30 courses and complete a senior 
thesis an option at brown while engineers are required to take 
36 
</TEXT>
