<TEXT>
lawyers for union carbide corp today asked 
district court judge mw deo to remove himself from hearing 
indias 3 billion suit against the company for negligence in the 
1984 bhopal gas disaster 
lawyers for the indian government and victims of the leak the 
worlds worst industrial accident criticized the move as a 
delaying tactic 
the request was made by carbide lawyer fali nariman who 
contended in a petition that deo showed bias by ordering on dec 17 
that the corporation pay interim relief to victims before 
ruling on the merits of the suit 
the order was not only without jurisdiction but wholly 
arbitrary perverse and displays a complete prejudgment nariman 
said 
deo said the petition was unusual since such requests normally 
are made to a higher court but he scheduled a hearing for june 16 
on the matter 
the court recesses saturday for summer vacation and returns june 
13 
nearly 3000 people were killed and at least 20000 seriously 
injured when toxic methylisocyanate leaked from a pesticide plant 
run by a subsidiary of union carbide in bhopal on dec 3 1984 
bhopal is the capital of the central indian state of madhya 
pradesh 
deo is the fourth judge in the case the first was promoted to 
the high court and the second withdrew after a serious auto injury 
the third judge gs patel was transferred to another court by 
the indian government after it was disclosed that he had filed a 
claim in the case 
vepa sarthy a lawyer for the indian government accused union 
carbide of filing its petition with a view to delay the case 
lawyer vibhuti jha a courtrecognized intervener on behalf 
of voluntary relief organizations helping the gas victims urged 
the judge to reject carbides request he described it as stalling 
deos december order that union carbide pay interim relief to 
the gas victims was upheld by the madhya pradesh high court on 
april 4 the high court set the amount of payment at 192 million 
union carbide earlier this week asked the high court to review 
its decision 
the multinational company with headquarters in danbury conn 
also faces criminal charges in connection with the gas leak 
india contends the gas leak was caused by negligence the 
company has said it resulted from sabotage by a distruntled 
employee 
