a recent epidemic of deformed birds and 
a decline in the populations of certain bird types is a warning the 
earth may still be on the path to ecological disaster a leading 
ecologist warned 
there may yet be a silent spring in our future stanford 
university ecologist paul r ehrlich told a gathering thursday at 
the peninsula conservation center in palo alto about 30 miles 
south of san francisco 
ehrlich coauthor of the birders handbook a natural 
history of north american birds referred to rachel carsons 
prediction of environmental deterioration in her 1962 book silent 
spring 
the book said to have galvanized the us environmental 
movement warned that if pesticide spraying was not controlled 
entire ecological system could be thrown out of balance 
because pesticide use is now better regulated some of the 
danger has passed said ehrlich but like the miners canaries 
of old birds still serve as an environmental early warning 
system 
the clearing of us forests has led to a decline in warblers 
and other songbirds and toxics found in agricultural runoff are 
creating mutations among other bird species ehrlich said 
birds are quite sensitive to poisons in the environment and 
as a result an epidemic of deformed birds has recently hit the 
united states said ehrlich 
it appears to be connected with high concentrations of 
selenium mercury and other toxic elements in agricultural runoff 
and drainage from mines and power plants he said 
duck and loon populations have declined in areas where acid rain 
has destroyed the aquatic insects fish and other prey in lakes and 
marshes where birds breed he said 
