<TEXT>
medicares fortunes have improved and its 
trust fund now is not likely to run out of cash until the year 
2005 while the social security old age fund should be solvent 
until the middle of the 21st century the systems trustees told 
congress on friday 
the 2005 date is three years later than was forecast a year ago 
the trustees including three reagan cabinet members said 
social securitys old age fund also had achieved robust gains and 
predicted it will have enough funds to cover expenditures for 
about 60 years into the future 
the board said medicares trust fund grew by nearly 14 billion 
in calendar 1987 and finished the year with reserves of 537 
billion 
assuming moderate economic conditions the hospital insurance 
reserves were forecast to grow to nearly 153 billion over the next 
decade before dwindling to nothing in the year 2005 
the trustees urged congress to take early remedial measures to 
bring future medicare costs and finance into balance and to 
avoid the need for later potentially precipitous changes 
they said the shortfall could be covered by a 14 percent cut in 
benefits a 16 percent increase in the medicare tax or a 
combination of both 
in the early 1980s the trustees warned medicares trust fund 
would go bankrupt in the 1990s its financial picture has improved 
partly as a result of federal constraints on hospital payments 
the medicare program provides hospital insurance for 28 million 
americans 65 or older and 3 million disabled workers under 65 the 
program took in 641 billion in payroll taxes and other income in 
1987 and paid out 503 billion 
the social security old age fund on the verge of bankruptcy 
just a few years ago experienced even more robust growth it grew 
by 23 billion in 1987 reflecting the continuing growth in the 
economy the trustees said and finished the year with 621 
billion in reserves 
the old age program had income of 2107 billion and 
disbursements of 1877 billion in 1987 
the disability fund took in 203 billion but paid out 214 
billion and finished 1987 with 67 billion in reserve 
the old age and disability programs pay benefits to 38 million 
retirees and disabled workers 
the trustees said the 11 billion drop in the disability 
reserve was due to a growing number of people awarded disability 
benefits 
the trustees said they expected the number of aids victims 
drawing disability to grow rapidly through 1991 
but so far they said due to the extremely high mortality 
rates the total number of disabled workers currently receiving 
benefits has not increased greatly as a result of aids 
the combined old age and disability funds now equal to about 
three months benefit payments are expected to bulge rapidly over 
the next 27 years peaking at more than 12 trillion 2 trillion 
in todays dollars in 2015 that would be enough to pay benefits 
for more than five years 
the old age and disability funds are expected to grow by 40 
billion this year 46 billion in 1989 and 75 billion in 1992 
the trustees said the next social security advisory council 
should examine what the proper level of fund accumulation should 
be some politicians including rep jack kemp rny have 
called for lowering the payroll tax instead of building up a huge 
reserve 
otis r bowen the secretary of health and human services said 
those reserves will be needed to meet the financial obligations 
of the program in the next century when the young workers of today 
become eligibile for social security 
the plan is to dig into that reserve after 2015 to help pay 
retirement for the socalled baby boom generation until the funds 
are exhausted in 2048 the trustees said 
then the system would need to raise taxes or lower benefits to 
stay on an even keel the actuarial deficit over 75 years is just 
058 percent of taxable payroll the equivalent of a 029 percent 
increase in the payroll tax on workers and employers 
in 1960 there were 51 workers paying taxes for each 
beneficiary today there are 34 workers per beneficiary the 
trustees said the ratio will fall gradually to 3to1 by the year 
2010 and then 2to1 by the year 2030 
they predicted a 38 percent benefit increase next january with 
increases of 4 percentplus over the next five years 
they also forecast that the maximum amount of wages subject to 
the social security and medicare tax now 45000 will rise to 
46500 in 1989 48600 in 1990 and 57000 in 1993 the tax 
climbs from 751 percent to 765 percent in 1990 
the trustees also forecast scenarios under optimistic and 
pessimistic economic and demographic conditions their estimate of 
moderate conditions however is the one usually relied on by 
congress 
this middlerange forecast assumes longrange growth of 14 
percent a year in real wages inflation of 4 percent interest 
rates of 6 percent and unemployment at 6 percent 
the trustees report to congress was five weeks overdue 
james a baker iii the secretary of the treasury is the 
managing trustee the others are bowen secretary of labor ann 
mclaughlin and two from the private sector mary falvey fuller and 
suzanne denbo jaffe 
</TEXT>
