<TEXT>
the presidential task force appointed last 
fall to study the october stock market crash says progress toward 
reforming the market should not be sidetracked by turf battles 
among federal regulators 
a statement released thursday by the new york office of nicholas 
f brady a wall street investment banker who headed the 
presidential panel said the flaws in the mechanisms that govern 
our equity markets are still in place and must be addressed 
the statement said debate over market reform has concentrated 
on who should oversee the needed changes rather than on what 
should be reformed on which the statement said there is much 
more agreement 
selfinterest and turf battles among the regulators and 
exchanges cannot be allowed to stand in the way of necessary reform 
of a limited number of issues that cut across marketplaces it 
said 
the statement was released three days after brady met with a 
reagan administration working group which is formulating specific 
suggestions for reforming the markets 
that panel headed by treasury undersecretary george gould and 
comprising the chairmen of the federal reserve board securities 
and exchange commission and commodity futures trading commission 
is due to report to president reagan later this month 
according to sources familiar with the groups work it is 
unlikely to go along with the brady panels recommendation that the 
federal reserve or a coordinating committee of regulators should 
get authority to coordinate stock trading and stock index futures 
trading 
brady is backing legislation sponsored by senate banking 
committee chairman william proxmire dwis which would create a 
coordinating body chaired by the head of the federal reserve board 
the brady panels statement warned that it would be a mistake 
to abandon the development of appropriate legislation 
two sources who spoke on condition of anonymity said it 
appeared that the working group was making progress toward an 
agreement on coordinated circuit breakers which would halt 
trading when markets take an extreme dive or climb 
however the sources said there was less agreement on 
coordinating margins which set the amount of money required to 
make an investment in either the futures or stock market although 
the margins work differently in each market they currently are 
lower in the futures markets 
the five members of the brady task force said it is essential 
to harmonize the level of margins adding that margin setting was 
too important to leave to the exchanges 
the federal reserve sets margins for stocks and stock options 
while individual futures exchanges set their own margins 
in the world of one market it makes little sense to provide 
investors with different degrees of leverage depending on whether 
they enter through the stock or derivative futures door the 
panel wrote 
regarding circuit breakers the brady commission said it was 
encouraged by the work of the new york stock exchange and the 
chicago mercantile exchange toward coordinating market halts 
however it warned that circuit breakers should not be set at 
levels that cause them to be triggered frequently 
it also criticized a new york stock exchange move to restrict 
computerized program trading when the dow jones average of 30 
industrial stocks swings up or down by 50 points 
that kind of circuit breaker it said runs the risk of 
disconnecting the marketplaces an outcome we believe would 
destabilize the market as a whole 
the brady panel praised the efforts of the exchanges to expand 
trading capacity easing the possibility that extremely high 
trading volume would cause a breakdown of the market 
however let us not fool ourselves merely increasing market 
capacity will not assure that a repeat of october will be 
averted it said 
in addition to brady head of dillon read amp co the panel 
members are robert kirby chairman of capital guardian trust co 
john opel former ibm chairman james c cotting navistar 
international corp chairman and howard stein dreyfus corp 
chairman 
