months 
this country is fed up with whitecollar crime and wants 
judges to start treating whitecollar criminals like the crooks 
they really are rule said antitrust crimes are nothing more 
than sophisticated larceny 
newly instituted federal sentencing guidelines require judges to 
sentence antitrust defendants to confinement for a minimum of four 
months 
in addition the guidelines require fines based on the volume of 
commerce attributable to the defendant an individual conspirator 
must be fined from four percent to 10 percent of the volume of the 
commerce done by him in goods or services that were affected by the 
conspiracy but not less than 20000 
for corporations and other organizations the guidelines provide 
for fines ranging from 20 percent to 50 percent of the volume of 
commerce done by the organization in goods or services affected by 
the violation but not less than 100000 the maximum corporate 
fine now is 1 million 
while we are now witnessing an increased willingness of judges 
to take antitrust felonies seriously some judges in the past have 
shown undue lenience toward antitrust criminals rule said 
rule said a recent study estimates that the justice departments 
prosecution of 52 pricefixing conspiracies from 1962 to 1980 
