strict sentencing guidelines imposed in 
november for federal crimes have been ruled unconstitutional by a 
panel of us district court judges in californias central 
district 
the federal judges voted 1410 thursday to reject the guidlines 
imposed by the us sentencing commission a sevenmember group 
formed by congress 
federal judges in maryland also have declared the guidelines 
unconstitutional individual judges elsewhere have disagreed on 
whether to implement the rules 
the department of justice wants to take this up to the supreme 
court on an expedited basis said assistant us attorney james 
berliner we look forward to a prompt resolution by that court 
the guidelines set up a prescribed range of penalties based on 
the severity of the crime and the defendants background although 
designed to make federal sentencing more uniform some jurists say 
they unfairly restrict a judges ability to select the best 
sentence in individual cases 
the decision here affects 32 federal judges working in the 
sevencounty central district which extends from san luis obispo 
to san clemente 
the majority opinion written by judge a andrew hauk attacked 
the constitutionality of the guidelines in two areas 
he wrote that the sentencing restrictions violate a defendants 
right to due process by barring judges from their traditional and 
fundamental ability to exercise discretion 
they also violate constitutional separation of powers among the 
three branches of government because three federal judges serve on 
the sentencing commission formed by congress hauk wrote 
