<TEXT>
twentyfive states asked a federal appeals 
court friday to review a new transportation department regulation 
concerning air fare advertising that they contend undercuts state 
consumerprotection laws 
the petition for review filed with the us circuit court of 
appeals here said the march 10 order allowing airlines to advertise 
air fares without including taxes fees and other surcharges in the 
total price conflicts with the states interpretation of their 
own consumer protection statutes 
the order will undercut the protections provided to consumers 
to know the total price of air transportation the petition said 
the states contended that the total advertised price should 
include foreign departure taxes customs fees immigration fees 
security fees and other charges imposed by government agencies 
each of the states interprets its consumer protection statutes 
that it is a deceptive practice for airlines to advertise a price 
to be paid by a consumer for air transportation without disclosing 
the total price to be paid for the air transportation the 
petition said 
the transportation department order allows the airlines to 
advertise the air fare at the top of ads without including the fees 
in the total price provided that the fees are mentioned in 
legible readable type at the bottom of the ad 
the petition was filed by the states of alaska arkansas 
california colorado connecticut indiana kansas maine 
maryland massachusetts michigan minnesota missouri montana 
new hampshire new jersey new york north dakota pennsylvania 
rhode island tennessee texas washington wisconsin and vermont 
</TEXT>
