<TEXT>
fixedrate home mortgages after falling since 
the october stock market crash headed higher in april the 
government said friday 
the federal home loan bank board which regulates savings 
institutions said its nationwide average for conventional 30year 
fixedrate mortgages on single family homes rose to 1048 percent 
in early april up from 1033 percent in march 
it was the first increase in the bank boards monthly average 
since october interest rates began falling after the stock market 
crash as the federal reserve board pumped money into the economy to 
guard against a recession 
market analysts believe the fed tightened the money supply in 
march pushing rates higher as it shifted its emphasis from 
recessionfighting to dampening fears of inflation 
the bank board survey said rates for the most popular type of 
oneyear adjustablerate mortgages those with limits on how much 
the rate can increase dropped slightly from 864 percent in march 
to 862 percent in april 
it was the first time in six months that the spread between 
rates for the two types of mortgages has widened however the 
april margin of 186 percent was still much smaller than the record 
242 percent gap in october 
interest rates are on the rise once again particularly for 
fixedrate mortgages said warren lasko executive vice president 
of the mortgage bankers association of america this reflects a 
general uptrend over the past few weeks in the bond markets and 
renewed fears of inflation 
the bank board numbers really reflect the world of a month ago 
and since then rates have gone still higher he said adding that 
the april unemployment report showing the jobless rate dropping to 
54 percent for the first time since 1974 will fan inflation fears 
and is only going to make things worse 
however lasko said we dont think this rise in rates will 
throttle homebuying if anything it will cause people to buy 
sooner to take advantage of rates while they are still attractive 
according to a separate weekly report by the federal home loan 
mortgage corp 30year fixedterm rates rose this week to 1032 
percent up from 1028 percent a week ago those averages are lower 
than the bank boards because they do not include addon fees 
known as points which are paid by borrowers 
the bank board also said the share of mortgage loans with 
adjustable rates fell below 50 percent for the first time since 
last july the adjustablerate share which peaked at 69 percent in 
december fell from 54 percent in march to 48 percent in april 
lasko said he expected that trend to reverse as the gap widens 
between fixed and adjustable rates 
