<TEXT>
two auxiliary roman catholic 
bishops and an apostolic administrator will be appointed in june as 
a step toward improved relations with the communist government 
church sources said friday 
the disclosure came after two vatican envoys archbishop 
francesco colasuonno and the rev john bukowski visited prague for 
talks with vladimir janku head of the state office for church 
affairs no details of the talks were reported 
both auxiliary bishops will serve under cardinal frantisek 
tomasek of prague the 88yearold catholic primate and the 
apostolic administrator will be assigned to trnava in slovakia 
apostolic administrators are considered titular bishops ranking 
below full bishops 
no names have been disclosed but church sources said privately 
the nominees were expected to be jan lebeda and antonin liska as 
auxiliary bishops and jan sokol as the apostolic administrator 
they said the auxiliary bishops probably would be ordained june 
11 and the trnava appointee june 12 by a vatican delegation led by 
cardinal achille silvestrini 
ten of czechoslovakias 13 dioceses still will not have full 
bishops no new bishops have been appointed since 1973 and the 
remaining three are over age 75 
janku was quoted thursday by the youth daily mlada fronta as 
saying the government seeks earnest solutions to disputed 
questions with the vatican 
his statement was seen as evidence of better relations with the 
holy see which have been strained by religious activism and 
disputes over choosing bishops 
the vatican refuses to accept candidates from the 
statesponsored clergy association pacem in terris which the 
vatican does not recognize 
in the interview janku said in principle we have already 
reached agreement on criteria for the selection of bishops 
the vatican has three requirements faithfulness to the 
church capability of pastoral care and moral purity we have a 
fourth requirement he should be a man loyal to the state 
