<TEXT>
a tentative contract covering 66000 
chrysler corp employees in 15 states was approved by the united 
auto workers 140member national chrysler council friday and goes 
next to the rank and file 
we believe it will be ratified overwhelmingly said uaw vice 
president marc stepp head of the unions chrysler department 
the twoyear jobprotecting contract reached wednesday would 
replace a threeyear pact that runs out sept 14 in 1990 all big 
three contracts will expire together for the first time in a 
decade boosting the uaws bargaining power 
the chrysler council approved the pact after a 5hour meeting 
a provision giving full chrysler seniority to former american 
motors corp workers in 1990 was deleted by the council before it 
gave its approval gm acquired amc last year 
the contract which also covers 65000 retirees at the no 3 
automaker will be presented to union members for ratification on 
wednesday 
it is patterned on the contracts in place at ford motor co and 
general motors for the first time since 1979 when the uaw granted 
chrysler deep concessions to help rescue the automaker from near 
bankruptcy 
the contract prevents further plant closings and layoffs for any 
reason other than slow sales halves the attrition rate and 
restricts the automakers ability to transfer work to outside 
suppliers or foreign countries 
it also contains lumpsum bonuses equal to 3 percent of wages 
each year and provides profitsharing to chrysler workers for the 
first time 
it should pass the job security is there that was the most 
important issue said mike allen a union official with uaw local 
624 in syracuse ny 
stepp said the settlement and approval by the council had 
brought to an end months of bitter conflict that led the two sides 
to seek a solution by holding early contract talks theres peace 
in the valley he said 
unlike the ford and gm agreements the chrysler pact includes a 
1000 signing bonus and prevents chrysler from paying executives 
cash or stock bonuses in years when the profitsharing formula 
generates no payout for workers 
in addition it covers 1200 former amc workers still on the job 
in wisconsin after a 5500worker amc assembly plant in kenosha 
wis closes at years end 
</TEXT>
