<TEXT>
physicians have broken a threeyear japanese 
moratorium on organ transplants caused by controversy over the 
definition of donors death by transferring kidneys to two 
recipients medical officials said friday 
physicians at the shinrakuen hospital in niigata 160 miles 
northwest of tokyo removed the kidneys thursday from the body of a 
braindead male donor after receiving permission from his 
relatives a hospital official said speaking on condition of 
anonymity 
although japanese physicians have performed about 150 kidney 
transplants in the past thursdays operations were the first 
transplants of major organs conducted in japan since 1985 
organ transplants came to a halt that year after doctors at 
tsukuba university near tokyo were accused both of murdering a 
patient to extract his kidneys and pancreas and of injuring the 
recipient who died about one year after the operation 
in january the japan medical association opened the way again 
for transplants by deciding that the cessation of brain function is 
a sufficient criterion for death opponents of transplants have 
argued that under japanese law human life comes to an end only 
when the heart stops and all visible signs of life have disappeared 
the science council of japan backed the medical associations 
decision in february after a yearlong study by the councils 
special medical committee 
heart transplants have an even shorter history in japan the 
countrys only recorded heart transplant was conducted in 1967 by 
dr juro wada of sapporo medical college wada was later accused of 
sacrificing the life of the donor the recipient died 82 days after 
the operation 
