<TEXT>
mutual fund lists appearing in newspapers are 
carrying some new footnotes 
because of the growing complexity and variation in commissions 
dividends and fees for mutual funds the associated press has 
revised the footnotes it uses to denote those aspects of funds 
for instance an nl designation in place of an offering 
price is being used in the daily list now only when a mutual fund 
truly is no load that is there is no sales commission to buy 
into the fund or to redeem shares and get out 
the weekly mutual fund tables will denote noload funds with an 
n footnote after the name 
some funds do not charge a commission when you buy shares but do 
charge a fee if the shares are sold within a certain period a 
condition called a contingentdeferredsales charge those funds 
are shown having an offering price the same as the net asset value 
nav and carry a new footnote r after the name of the fund 
some funds charge an annual fee to cover marketing expenses 
although they do not include the charge in their advertised sales 
fee that condition is denoted with a p footnote following the 
fund name 
funds that both have a contingentdeferredsales charge and 
charge a percentage of fund assets for marketing expenses now carry 
a t footnote 
footnotes also have been changed for denoting exdividend 
exdistribution and stock split or stock dividends 
previously all those conditions were represented by an x 
footnote now x designates an exdividend e means 
exdistribution of capital gains and s denotes a stock split or 
stock dividend 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
here is the explanation of the footnotes for the mutual funds 
list 
e ex capital gains distribution s stock dividend or split 
x ex cash dividend 
f previous days quote nln no frontend load or contingent 
deferred sales load p fund assets are used to pay for 
distribution costs12b1 plan r redemption fee or contingent 
deferred sales load may apply t both p and r 
</TEXT>
