among the precious metals platinum futures showed the sharpest 
reaction to aprils 54 percent jobless rate the platinum contract 
for delivery in july jumped 540 to 52660 a troy ounce on the 
new york mercantile exchange 
but silver gained too and analysts said the net impact of the 
unemployment report on the metals markets was positive 
im not surprised theres a little jockeying going on with 
silver and platinum higher and gold a little lower maybe monday 
itll be the reverse said richard levine vice president of 
precious metals and foreign exchange trading with elders futures 
inc 
the reports implications for a robust economy supported notions 
that consumer prices are bound to rise which could stir more 
demand for precious metals analysts said 
platinum prices got an extra boost because a growing economy 
would mean greater industrial demand for the metal 
some parts of the report have to be viewed as having potential 
for inflation said craig sloane an analyst in new york with 
smith barney harris upham amp co 
work hours were up hourly wage was up overtime hours were 
up said levine were talking about an economy thats really 
moving along in terms of employment 
at the commodity exchange in new york gold settled 170 to 
180 lower with june at 44530 a troy ounce silver was 15 cents 
to 22 cents higher with may at 6381 a troy ounce 
