<TEXT>
the federal government on friday charged 
ef hutton amp co inc in connection with an alleged 
moneylaundering scheme that helped organized crime figures and 
businessmen conceal at least 532000 from the internal revenue 
service 
hutton was expected to plead guilty to the three felony counts 
of conspiracy and money laundering us attorney lincoln c almond 
said 
two former hutton brokers were also named in documents known as 
a criminal information filed in us district court here one of 
the brokers stephen s fusco died shortly after the investigation 
began and almond said charges against the other brian j lareau 
46 of jamestown would be filed next week 
the charges accuse hutton of failing to report at least 532000 
in currency transactions through its providence office federal law 
requires that cash transactions of greater than 10000 must be 
reported to the irs 
the people for whom the transaction were allegedly made were not 
named in the past almond has said up to 12 million was 
involved some of it from organizedcrime figures and some from 
businessmen 
hutton was acquired last year by shearson lehman brothers inc 
and the company is now known as shearson lehman hutton inc a 
shearson spokesman michael o neill said the company would 
acquiesce to the charges 
there was an agreement reached about a month and a half ago at 
which hutton agreed to a criminal disposition oneill said the 
filing of the charges he said was the next logical step 
oneill said the charges would not interfere with huttons 
current operations its an old matter and the principals have 
long since left the firm he said 
hutton faces up to 101 million in fines 
almond called the alleged scheme a major problem existing in 
the providence office of hutton he said he did not know of any 
wrongdoing at other hutton offices 
he declined to give details of the alleged crimes on friday but 
said they would be spelled out after a court hearing on may 16 
according to the criminal information fusco allegedly accepted 
cash in amounts greater than 10000 from clients and directed 
other hutton employees to take the cash to providence banks and buy 
cashiers checks in denominations smaller than 10000 
the cashiers checks would then be deposited in the customers 
accounts and used to purchase bearer bonds which would be redeemed 
through intermediaries to conceal their true ownership the 
information charged 
almond said the investigation of hutton began in the summer of 
1985 after the probe was completed last summer the justice 
department and the company began several months of negotiations 
which led to the charges being filed 
fusco who died of cancer in late 1985 committed the more 
egregious offenses almond said lareau was an offshoot of 
that 
no other individuals will be charged in the case almond said a 
corporation can be held criminally liable for the acts of its 
employees but there was no evidence other hutton employees 
participated in the alleged crimes he said 
under securities and exchange commission rules a felony 
conviction could result in the total suspension of investment 
services 
shearson said last month it expected to receive waivers from the 
sec that would allow it to continue business 
last october the sec found that hutton had violated provisions 
of the sec law and rules relating to financial record keeping and 
reporting of currency transactions 
as a result hutton was censured and directed to report to the 
sec on policies and procedures regarding the receipt of cash 
deposits and to adopt surveillance procedures to monitor deposits 
of multiple bank checks 
